### What is Recursion?

Recursion occurs when a function calls itself. Every recursive function needs a base case to prevent infinite recursion.

```dart
int factorial(int n) {
  // Base case
  if (n <= 1) return 1;
  // Recursive case
  return n * factorial(n - 1);
}

void main() {
  print(factorial(5)); // 120
}
```

### Classic Examples

#### Fibonacci Sequence

```dart
int fibonacci(int n) {
  if (n <= 1) return n;
  return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
}

void main() {
  for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    print('fib($i) = ${fibonacci(i)}');
  }
}
```

#### Sum of List

```dart
int sumList(List<int> numbers, int index) {
  if (index >= numbers.length) return 0;
  return numbers[index] + sumList(numbers, index + 1);
}

void main() {
  var nums = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
  print(sumList(nums, 0)); // 15
}
```

### Recursion vs Iteration

| Aspect | Recursion | Iteration |
|--------|-----------|-----------|
| Code | Often more concise | Usually longer |
| Performance | More overhead (stack frames) | More efficient |
| Stack limit | Limited by call stack | No stack limit |
| Readability | Better for tree/graph problems | Better for simple loops |

### Tail Recursion

Dart does not guarantee tail-call optimization, but you can structure recursion to be tail-recursive:

```dart
int factorialTail(int n, [int acc = 1]) {
  if (n <= 1) return acc;
  return factorialTail(n - 1, n * acc);
}

void main() {
  print(factorialTail(5)); // 120
}
```

### Recursion on Collections

```dart
void printReversed(List list, [int? index]) {
  index ??= list.length - 1;
  if (index < 0) return;
  print(list[index]);
  printReversed(list, index - 1);
}

void main() {
  printReversed([1, 2, 3, 4, 5]);
}
```

> **Key Point:** Recursion is ideal for problems with recursive structure (trees, graphs, divide-and-conquer). For simple loops, iteration is usually more efficient.

